ALLOYS

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 01.jpg}}
1.—(Heycock & Neville, Phil. Trans.) Bronze containing 23.3% of tin. Slowly cooled. Magnified 18 diameters. Dark parts are rich in copper, light parts in tin.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 02.jpg}}
2.—(Ewing & Rosenhain, Phil. Trans.) Lead-tin eutectic. Magnified 750 diameters.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 03.jpg}}
3.—(F. Osmond.) Silver-copper [copper=15%, silver=85%] reheated to purple colour. Magnified 600 diameters.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 04.jpg}}
4.—(Heycock & Neville, Phil. Trans.) Copper-tin [tin 27.7%] chilled at 731° C. before complete solidification. Magnified 18 diameters. Blacks rich, whites less rich in copper.

GUN-MAKING

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 05.jpg}}
5.—Gun steel, C.=0.30%. From top of ingot as cast, magnified 29 diameters. Whites, ferrite; blacks, carbide.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 06.jpg}}
6.—Gun steel, C.=0.30%. From bottom of ingot as cast, magnified 29 diameters. Whites, ferrite; blacks, carbide.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 07.jpg}}
7.—Gun steel, C.=0.30%. Top of ingot, forged and annealed, magnified 29 diameters. Whites, ferrite; blacks, carbide.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 08.jpg}}
8.—Gun steel, C.=0.30%. Bottom of ingot, forged and annealed, magnified 29 diameters. Whites, ferrite; blacks, carbide.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 09.jpg}}
9.—Gun steel, C.=0.30%. Forged and annealed, magnified 1000 diameters, showing pearlite.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 10.jpg}}
10.—Gun steel, C. = 0.30%. Oil hardened and annealed, magnified 50 diameters.

IRON AND STEEL

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 11.jpg}}
11.—(Osmond.) Pearlite, steel (carbon about 1%) forged and annealed at 800° C. Magnified 1000 diameters.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 12.jpg}}
12.—(Stoughton.) Meshes of pearlite in a network of ferrite, from hypo-eutectoid steel. Magnified 250 diameters.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 13.jpg}}
13.—(Stoughton.) Meshes of pearlite in a network of cementite from hyper-eutectoid steel. Magnified 250 diameters.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 14.jpg}}
14.—(Osmond & Cartaud.) Martensite. Magnified 250 diameters.

{{IMG:Britannica Alloys Plate Figure 15.jpg}}
15.—(Osmond.) Martensite (black) in austensite (white). Steel (carbon about 1.5%) quenched at 1050° C. in ice-cold water. Magnified 250 diameters.
